
<p>Collateral weighted average price (WAP*) is quite useful for a quick snapshot of collateral credit risks.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full is-resized"><img loading="lazy" src="https://clopremium.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/image-96.png" alt="" class="wp-image-7830" width="724" height="445" srcset="https://clopremium.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/image-96.png 702w, https://clopremium.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/image-96-300x184.png 300w, https://clopremium.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/image-96-364x225.png 364w" sizes="(max-width: 724px) 100vw, 724px" /></figure>



<p>That said, this metric has its limitations.&nbsp;First and foremost, WAP could be&nbsp;<em>artificially</em>&nbsp;inflated due to trading. CLO managers may have crystallised portfolio losses by trading out of poorly performing assets. On the other hand, some managers might have built quality par, which could help soften the negative MTM impact. Be that as it may, the quality of each portfolio varies from one deal to another. One has to look at&nbsp;<a href="https://clopremium.co.uk/featured-us-clo-manager-scoring-based-on-total-mvinterest-return-alpha-updated/">the entirety of the manager’s performance since inception</a>, including the interest performance component and adjustments for the different market conditions. The WAP metric is a point-in-time metric, so it does not measure investment return performance over a period of time.</p>



<p>* Cash is included in the calculation</p>



